04443nam a22005895i 9780773557673DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2019401273  a97807735576737 a10.1515/97807735576732doi  a(DE-B1597)656999  a(OCoLC)1082521925  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aBX1529b.C36 2019 4aD622b.C378 2019 7aHIS0370502bisacsh04a940.47809442231 aCarter, Karen E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScandal in the Parish :bPriests and Parishioners Behaving Badly in Eighteenth-Century France /cKaren E. Carter. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v28400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPriest, Behaving Badly -- tParishioners, Also Behaving Badly -- tScandalous Sacraments -- tThe Holiness of the Place -- tThe Affairs of the Curés -- tDisturbing the Peace -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1770, the priest Nicolas Vernier was accused of neglecting church services, inappropriate behaviour in the confessional, financial improprieties, and affairs with the village schoolmistresses. In a contentious church court case, parishioners described all of their priest's wrongdoings, and in turn, he detailed many of theirs. Ultimately, Vernier finished his career as a cathedral canon in another diocese. Scandal in the Parish recounts Vernier's story and many similar eighteenth-century cases. In fascinating detail that reveals essential facets of rural religion during the Catholic Reformation period, Karen Carter considers French lay people's relationship with their parish curé, who governed and influenced so much of their religious practice. Although the priest's role as purveyor of God's grace through the sacraments was secure as long as he performed his duties appropriately, priests who were unable to navigate the pressures and high expectations put on them by their superiors and parishioners risked broken relationships, public disturbances of the peace, and even prosecution. These scandals, Carter demonstrates, tell us much about rural parish life, the processes of negotiation and accommodation between curés and their parishioners, and ongoing religious reforms and enforcement throughout the eighteenth century. An engaging venture into the world of the parish that highlights the centrality of the priest-parishioner relationship, Scandal in the Parish reveals the attitudes and practices of ordinary people who were active agents in their religious and spiritual lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aParisheszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aPeasantsxReligious lifezFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aRural clergyzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aScandalszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773557673?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773557673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773557673/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles